The first symbol of the string is t5.  
In this grammar the only non‑terminal that can emit the terminal t5 is NT25 (NT25 → 't5').  
Because of that, any successful derivation for the start symbol S must use the only production whose left component is NT25, namely  

 S → NT25 NT27  

and NT25 must take its single–terminal branch NT25 → 't5'.  
Consequently, the remaining 30 terminals

 t70 t60 t37 t60 t1 t68 t7 t45 t56 t25 t6 t41 t49 t35 t24 t42 t45 t16 t61 t46 t9 t68 t41 t49 t35 t61 t45 t2 t34 t61

have to be generated by the non‑terminal NT27.

NT27 has only four kinds of productions (no unit productions and no ε‑rules):

  1. NT27 → NT27 NT2  
  2. NT27 → NT3  NT27  
  3. NT27 → NT19 NT17  
  4. NT27 → NT25 NT7

Hence, the first terminal that NT27 produces must come from NT27, NT3, NT19 or NT25.

The first terminal of the required remainder is t70, and in the grammar t70 can be produced only by NT29 (NT29 → 't70').  
Thus the leftmost branch inside NT27 has to reach NT29 before producing anything else.

• If NT27 uses rule 4 (NT27 → NT25 NT7), the first terminal comes from NT25.  
 NT25 can only start with t5, t18, t19 or t38 – never t70.  
 So rule 4 cannot be used for the desired string.

• If NT27 uses rule 3 (NT27 → NT19 NT17), the first terminal comes from NT19.  
 The only direct terminals of NT19 are t34, t50 and t9.  
 To reach t70, NT19 would have to begin with a recursive NT27, which again leads us back to the same situation; no new option appears, and NT19 itself cannot start with t70.

• If NT27 uses rule 1 (NT27 → NT27 NT2), the leftmost terminal is produced by the left NT27, so we are in the same situation as at the top level; we eventually must fall into one of the other three rules, none of which can lead to t70 as just shown.

• If NT27 uses rule 2 (NT27 → NT3 NT27), the first terminal is produced by NT3.  
 NT3 can place NT29 on the left only by the productions NT3 → NT29 NT5 or NT3 → NT29 NT1, therefore the two left‑most terminals­ it outputs are  

  t70 followed by the first terminal of NT5 or NT1.

 NT5 can begin with t24, t7, t1 or t26, and NT1 can begin with t24, t41 or t2 – neither can emit t60.  
 But the second symbol of the required remainder is t60, which can only come from NT6.  
 Hence the prefix t70 t60 cannot be produced by NT3.

Because every possible first‑step expansion for NT27 has been examined and none of them can yield the prefix t70 t60, NT27 cannot generate the 30‑symbol suffix.  
Therefore the entire string cannot be derived from S, and it is not in the language of the grammar.

No

Every terminal that appears in the required string is produced directly by at least one non‑terminal of the grammar:

• t24  → NT5 | NT1 | NT16  
• t31  → NT14  
• t29  → NT24 | NT26  
• t11  → NT17  
• t43  → NT15 | NT3  
• t69  → NT9  
• t19  → NT25  
• t46  → NT21  
• t65  → NT13 | NT21  
• t32  → NT23  
• t22  → NT17 | NT7  
• t55  → NT20 | NT6  
• t41  → NT1  
• t45  → NT23  
• t26  → NT5 | NT12  
• t7   → NT5 | NT14  
• t5   → NT25  
• t6   → NT16 | NT18 | NT8  
• t61  → NT18  
• t17  → NT24  
• t18  → NT25  
• t25  → NT24  
• t70  → NT29  
• t1   → NT5  
• t42  → NT0  
• t47  → NT3  
• t44  → NT9  
• t50  → NT19  
• t2   → NT1  

Thus every token is accessible.

The start symbol S can expand to two large sub‑phrases, for example through  

S → NT25 NT27  

Both NT25 and NT27 are heavily recursive (each can eventually reach every other “helper’’ non‑terminal that appears above, e.g. NT25 → NT24 NT25, NT25 → NT2 NT15, NT27 → NT27 NT2, NT27 → NT3 NT27, …).  
Because they (and the non‑terminals they reach) contain no ε‑productions but do contain rules of the form X → YZ as well as all the needed 1‑token rules, they can be built up to produce any desired finite sequence of terminals, simply by recursing until the required length is obtained and then closing the derivation with the appropriate single‑terminal productions.

Consequently, NT25 can generate the first part of the 41‑token string and NT27 the remainder (for instance, 20 and 21 tokens respectively), giving a complete derivation from S.  Since every symbol in the target string can be produced along such a path, the whole string lies in the language of the grammar.

Yes

The first word of the string is `t38`.  
In the grammar, a terminal `t38` can only be produced by the non‑terminals NT12 or NT25.

Examine the five possible first productions of the start symbol S:

1. S → NT24 NT0  (the first word would have to come from NT24)  
   – NT24 can start with the terminals {t29, t71, t58, t17, t53, t37, t25} or with the first
     words of NT9, NT16, NT26, NT0, NT6, NT13.  
   – None of these possibilities is `t38`.  
   ⇒ impossible.

2. S → NT10 NT13  (the first word comes from NT10)  
   – The only way NT10 can start with `t38` is through the rule  
     NT10 → NT12 NT27 with NT12 → `t38`.  
   – The second word of the string is `t59`; it would have to be the first word generated
     by NT27.  But NT27 can start only with NT25, NT19 or NT3, whose possible
     first terminals are {t38, t19, t18, t5, t34, t50, t9, t47, t43}.  
     `t59` is not among them.  
   ⇒ impossible.

3. S → NT15 NT10  (the first word comes from NT15)  
   – NT15 can start with the terminals {t43, t59}.  
   – It cannot start with `t38`.  
   ⇒ impossible.

4. S → NT14 NT9  (the first word comes from NT14)  
   – NT14 can start only with {t31, t7}.  
   – Not `t38`.  
   ⇒ impossible.

5. S → NT25 NT27  (the first word comes from NT25)  
   – NT25 can indeed generate `t38` directly (NT25 → `t38`).  
   – If NT25 produces only that single token, the second word of the string, `t59`,
     must be the first word produced by NT27.  
     As noted above, NT27 cannot start with `t59`.  
   – NT25 could try to generate a longer prefix, but every production of NT25 that
     begins with another non‑terminal (NT24, NT4, NT19) leads to first terminals that
     are never `t38`.  Hence the only way to get the initial `t38` from NT25 is the
     one‑token production, which fails on the second word.  
   ⇒ impossible.

Since all possible first productions for S are incompatible with the initial part
of the given string, the grammar cannot derive the string.
